The `==` operator is used to check for reference equality, which means that it compares the memory address of two objects to see if they are the same. This operator is commonly used to compare objects of the same type, such as numbers, strings, and dates.

On the other hand, the `.equals()` method is used to compare the actual contents of an object, regardless of its memory address. It compares the value of each field in the object and returns a boolean value indicating whether the two objects are equal or not.

When should you use `==` and when should you use `.equals()`?

* Use `==` to compare objects of the same type, such as two strings or two integers.
* Use `.equals()` to compare the actual contents of an object, regardless of its memory address.

For example, you can use `==` to compare two strings and see if they are equal:
```
String str1 = "Hello";
String str2 = "Hello";
if (str1 == str2) {
    System.out.println("The strings are equal.");
} else {
    System.out.println("The strings are not equal.");
}
```
On the other hand, you can use `.equals()` to compare the actual contents of two strings and see if they are equal:
```
String str1 = "Hello";
String str2 = "Hello";
if (str1.equals(str2)) {
    System.out.println("The strings are equal.");
} else {
    System.out.println("The strings are not equal.");
}
```
In summary, `==` is used to compare objects of the same type, while `.equals()` is used to compare the actual contents of an object, regardless of its memory address.

